q.#text:
If Nicias
							is not guilty, let him go; but if he is guilty, let him go for my sake;
							but let him go anyway.

note.#text:
The latter part of this has been suspected on account of the length.
							For the sentiment  Homer,  276-277; Horace, , iii. 6. 46;
							Aratus, , 123-127.

p.#text:
When two persons accepted him as arbiter, he took them to the sacred precinct
						of Athena of the Brazen House, and made them swear to abide by his decision;
						and when they had given their oaths, he said,

q.#text:
In Heaven's name do not, for it is not right;
							the fact is, I should have done that myself if I had been quick enough
							and brave enough.

quote.#text:
Lifeless to Pitane came, on his shield
						upborne, Thrasybulus; Seven the wounds he received, pierced by the Argive
						spears; All in the front did he show them; and him with his blood-stained
						body Tynnichus placed on the pyre, saying these words in his eld : &ldquo;
							Let the poor cowards be mourned, but with never a tear shall I bury You,
							my son, who are mine, yea, and are Sparta's as well.&rdquo;
